Why these corrections are better (compared to the old code)

1) Queue-node input load in main (instead of assigning split output to head)
- Better because the project data model is node-based stacks (t_queue/t_node).
- The old approach mixed int array parsing and node queue usage, causing type errors and hidden logic bugs.
- New flow guarantees every value becomes exactly one node via knot_me + k2q.

2) Duplicate check during insertion (append_value)
- Better because duplicates are rejected immediately at the source.
- The old late-stage duplicate checks depended on int-array sentinels and mismatched pointer types.
- Immediate rejection also simplifies error handling and avoids extra passes.

3) create_stacks allocation fix
- Better because writing to an uninitialized pointer is undefined behavior (crash risk).
- The corrected version allocates before assignment and returns NULL on failure.

4) decappler_two_point_o cleanup reset
- Better because freeing nodes without resetting head/tail/size leaves stale pointers.
- Resetting queue metadata prevents use-after-free style bugs in later code paths.

5) Move-operation guards (swp/push/scroll_down)
- Better because stack ops can now safely no-op on tiny/empty stacks.
- The old code could dereference NULL or invalid next/prev pointers in edge cases.
- This is critical for checker robustness too, where invalid op sequences must not segfault.

6) Correct char checks in split/parser (s[i] not NULL pointer compares)
- Better because char-vs-NULL comparisons are type bugs in C.
- Using char-aware checks removes warnings and reflects actual string semantics.

7) ft_error signature/format fixes
- Better because printf format placeholders now match passed arguments.
- The old version could print garbage or crash and failed strict compilation.

8) sortini pointer/API fixes
- Better because passing queue pointers vs values is now consistent with function signatures.
- The old code mixed s.a and s->a usage and called functions with wrong argument types.

9) Single rank-assignment call location
- Better because repeated ft_howMuchisPastrami calls are redundant and can hide ordering assumptions.
- Keeping ranking in one place (push_swap path) makes behavior predictable.

10) Mandatory-only build scope first
- Better because it isolates foundational bugs before enabling advanced modules.
- Reintroducing griddy/chunk/LIS later makes debugging incremental instead of combinatorial.
